{{Infobox political party |country = United Kingdom |name = Agricultural Party |colorcode = orange |logo = |leader = J. F. Wright |chairman = |foundation = 1931 |dissolution = 1940s |ideology = [[Empire free trade]] with agricultural protection |position = |international = |european = |europarl = |predecessor = |colours = |headquarters = Norfolk |merged = }}
The '''Agricultural Party''' was a minor [[political party]] in the [[United Kingdom]]. It was founded in 1931 as the '''Norfolk Farmers' Party''' but changed its name one week after its formation.<ref name="craig">[[F. W. S. Craig]], ''Minor Parties at British Parliamentary Elections''</ref> It initially had the support of the [[National Farmers Union (England and Wales)|National Farmers Union]], [[Lord Rothermere]] and [[Lord Beaverbrook]].<ref name="barberis">Peter Barberis, John McHugh and Mike Tyldesley, ''Encyclopedia of British and Irish Political Organizations''</ref>
The party called for [[Empire free trade]], agricultural protection, and the introduction of duties on food imports.<ref name="craig" /> It stood candidates in the [[United Kingdom general election, 1931|1931 general election]] and again in the [[East Fife by-election, 1933|East Fife by-election]] in 1933, but without success, and it lost its high-profile supporters. It appears to have been disbanded in the late 1940s.<ref name="barberis" />
