'''Esther Morris Leidolf''' is a medical sociologist,<ref name="jh-2008"/> an intersex activist, US-based writer, the founder of the MRKH Organization, and was the board secretary for the [[Intersex Society of North America]].<ref name="isna-2002">{{cite web | url = | title = Intersex Activists Respond to "The Vagina Monologues" | work = [[Intersex Society of North America]] | date = January 7, 2002  | accessdate = 2018-08-31}}</ref><ref name="ourbodies">{{cite web | url = https://www.ourbodiesourselves.org/our-story/contributors/esther-morris-leidolf/ | title = Esther Morris Leidolf | work = Our Bodies Our Selves | accessdate = 2018-08-31 }}</ref> 

== Career ==

Esther Morris Leidolf is a US-based medical sociologist and health worker,<ref name="jh-2008">{{Cite journal| doi = 10.1080/00918360801982074| issn = 0091-8369| volume = 54| issue = 3| pages = 233–242| last1 = Morris Leidolf| first1 = Esther| last2 = Curran| first2 = Megan| last3 = Scout| last4 = Bradford| first4 = Judith| title = Intersex Mental Health and Social Support Options in Pediatric Endocrinology Training Programs| journal = Journal of Homosexuality| date = May 2008 | url = http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/00918360801982074}}</ref> writer, the founder of the MRKH Organization, and was the board secretary for the now-defunct [[Intersex Society of North America]].<ref name="isna-2002" /><ref name="ourbodies" /> In her roles with ISNA and MRKH Organization, Morris Leidorf spoke at conferences and events, including the [[LGBTI Health Summit]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.intersexinitiative.org/news/000139.html | title = Intersex Prominently Featured in the LGBTI Health Summit | work = Intersex Initiative | date = Aug 22, 2004 | accessdate = 2018-08-31}}</ref> Her works include ''The Missing Vagina Monologue''.<ref>{{cite book | first = Brian | last = Still | title = Online Intersex Communities: Virtual Neighborhoods of Support and Activism | publisher = Cambia Press | date = 2008 | ISBN = 9781604975925 | page = 115}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal| doi = 10.4000/rccsar.558| issn = 1647-3175| issue = 6| last = Santos| first = Ana Lúcia| title = Beyond Binarism? Intersex as an Epistemological and Political Challenge*| journal = RCCS Annual Review| date = October 2014| url = http://journals.openedition.org/rccsar/558}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | first = Laura A. | last = Zaccone | title = Policing the Policing of Intersex Bodies: Softening the Lines in Title IX Athletic Programs | journal = Brooklyn Law Review | date = 2010 | issue = 76 | url =  http://brooklynworks.brooklaw.edu/blr/vol76/iss1/9}}</ref> She has stated, 

{{quotation|"Being born without a vagina was not my problem. Having to get one was the real problem<ref name="isna-2002" />}}

Alongside other activists, Morris Leidolf was critical of a 2006 shift in clinical language from intersex to [[disorders of sex development]].<ref>{{cite book | first = Georgiann | last = Davis | author-link = Georgiann Davis | title = Contesting Intersex: The Dubious Diagnosis | publisher = NYU Press | date = September 2015 | ISBN = 9781479887040 | page = 45}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | first = Michaela | last = Koch | title = Discursive Intersexions: Daring Bodies between Myth, Medicine, and Memoir | publisher = transcript Verlag | date = 2017 |ISBN = 9783839437056 |page = 138}}</ref> She also appears in the award-winning 2012 documentary [[Intersexion]].

